- Manual test (add detailed scripts or steps below)

```
mycli -h 127.0.0.1 -P 4000 -u root --no-warn << "EOF"
set global tidb_enable_alter_placement=on;
drop database if exists test;
create database test;
EOF

mycli -h 127.0.0.1 -P 4000 -u root --no-warn << "EOF"
create table test.t1 (a int) partition by hash(a) partitions 2;
create table test.t2 (a int);
alter table test.t1 alter partition p0 alter placement policy role=leader;
select * from information_schema.placement_policy;
EOF

$PDCTL config placement-rules show # p0 with a rule of 1 leader

mycli -h 127.0.0.1 -P 4000 -u root --no-warn << "EOF"
alter table test.t1 exchange partition p0 with table test.t2;
select * from information_schema.placement_policy;
EOF

$PDCTL config placement-rules show # GroupID changed to the id of t2

mycli -h 127.0.0.1 -P 4000 -u root --no-warn << "EOF"
alter table test.t1 exchange partition p0 with table test.t2;
select * from information_schema.placement_policy;
EOF

$PDCTL config placement-rules show # now, p0 has 1 leader, t2 has none
```

### Release note <!-- bugfixes or new feature need a release note -->

- Altering placement rule when exchanging partitions
